;
; A2 NON-VACUITY / TOTALITY control — decode_byte's Err path is genuinely reachable
;   and Ok values are real (decode is a TOTAL function: Ok or Err, never a panic).
;   Discharged by `ay`.
; Expected: sat  (a witness exists: some byte maps to the 0xFF sentinel => Err, and
;                 some byte maps to a valid 0..63 index => Ok — both branches live).
;
; FAITHFUL SOURCE (crates/aterm-codec/src/base64.rs:18-29, 219-225):
;   build_decode_table: table = [0xFF; 256]; then table[alphabet[i]] = i for i in 0..64.
;   decode_byte: let val = table[byte as usize];
;                if val == 0xFF { Err(InvalidByte) } else { Ok(val) }
;   So a byte that is NOT in the standard alphabet (e.g. '!'=33, ' '=32, '='=61)
;   maps to 0xFF and yields Err; an alphabet byte (e.g. 'A'=65 -> 0, '/'=47 -> 63)
;   yields Ok. This control proves BOTH branches are reachable (the unsat lemmas
;   would be vacuous if decode_byte could never reach a real value or an Err).
;
; This models the CONCRETE 256-entry STANDARD_DECODE table as a pure-BV ite-chain
; (byte -> table value), then asks ay for a witness satisfying both:
;   * exists an invalid byte: table[byte] == 0xFF   (Err path reachable)
;   * the same model pins a valid byte producing an in-range index (Ok path real).
(set-logic QF_BV)

(declare-const byte (_ BitVec 8))      ; the invalid (Err) witness byte

; STANDARD_DECODE[byte] as a pure-BV ite-chain. Default tail (byte 255) is 0xFF.
